description.value:
Fragment from a corner of a warp-faced plain weave, undyed, linen tunic (a) with tapestry (single warp threads) panel (b); Hitched warp fringe; On (a), c.2.2cm above the fringe, are bare warp threads and c.2.2cm above the bare threads are 8 ribs of 3 weft threads grouped (2 ribs/2 normal picks/2ribs); Warp (a): S spun linen, c.23tpc; Weft (a): S spun linen, c.13tpc; Edges: one plain selvedge and at the adjacent edge the fringe (c.2cm long), other edges cut; Sewing: (b) sewn to (a) with S spun Z ply linen thread, mosting hemming of turned under edges but also running stitch on two sides.

The applied, sqaure panel (b) is c.8.8cm above the fringe; Centre is mainly purple-coloured wool but with traces of worn outline design in undyed linen in flying thread brocading; Design of curling double ribbons forming a grid of 4 to 5 squares; Outer border of plain undyed linen; Warp: undyed, S spun wool?, c.13tpb; Weft: S spun linen & wool, c.60tpc; Edges: not visible as turned under

description.value: Fragmentary conical hair-net of undyed linen which is now straw-coloured to dark brown, patterned with lozenges produced by areas of denser and less dense netting. The hair-het is drawn into the central point by increasing the grouping together of the individual threads. Part of both sides of the opening is preserved with, on one side of a seam, a solid edge formed by two cords passing through short loops and longer loops on the other side; the draw string is now missing. A lock of human hair is preserved in the most matted area, and two selvedges and a separate brow band remain.  The linen warp stitch gauge is c. 12 threads per cm, being S-spun and Z-plied. Two seams were overcast with S-spun, Z-ply linen thread.

description.value: One irregular fragment of a brown woven goat hair bag decorated with a fringe of goat hair wrapped at intervals with blue, green, red, yellow and gold wool. The goat hair thread is 'z'-plied and the wrapping wool is 's'-spun. The weave is weft-faced at the top of the fragment and warp-faced at the edge of the fringed area. The fringe is twisted. The stitch gauge is warp 8 per 10mm and weft 8 per 10mm. The top 20mm of the top edge consist of 6 rows of countered twining. This is followed by 50mm of basketweave. Below this the warps hang loosely and are of irregular length. The longest is 310mm. At intervals each warp pair has been wrapped with coloured wool, (red, blue, green, yellow, cream, purple, burgundy and brown) in a figure '8' configuration. Wrapped areas are 10-15mm in size.  Before conservation, January 2007.

description.value: Two wall-hangings; linen and wool; decorated at the top with an undulating vine-stem, in the curves of which are bowls of flowers and fruit, bunches of grapes, nereids, standing birds and running, nimbed, leopards. description.value: Over thirty fragments of a golden brown, woven undyed flax tunic, fabric type L. The spinning direction of the warp and weft is 's' and the weave is plain and balanced. description.value:
Furnishing(?); fragment; One end of a small cloth, mainly plain linen. Three decorative stripes, in dark and light blue and undyed threads (from the fringe inwards, respectively 15, 4 and 1-3 cms wide); design of small dotted lozenges. In stripes, weft consists of passes of two complementary lats, each lat mostly passing over three threads, under two, over one, under two etc., but this course being reversed and adjusted to form lozenges. Simple tabby and compound tabby.
Warp: linen, S-spun, ca 13 threads/cm.
Weft: linen (undyed and pale blue), S-spun, cotton (undyed and dark blue), ca 12 picks/cm in plain areas, ca 14 passes/cm in stripes.
Edges: one simple fringe, two selvedge, 4th side fragmentary.

description.value: One irregular fragment of a heavy black, tan and redwoven rug made of goat hair, sheep wool and camel wool. One selvedge edge is present. The weave is warp-faced and all yarns are 2-ply.  The stitch gauge is warp 4 per 10mm and weft 14 per 10mm.The warp is made of 'z'-plied yarns most of which were grouped before being plied. The weft is made of various yarn scraps of different types including sheep wool and goat hair. The fragment has a central stripe 118mm wide. Within the central stripe are horizontal rows of dark brown triangles outlined in white. A single red triangle is located in the centre of each row and the rows are separated by white lines. This was bordered on either side by a stripe of undyed medium brown camel wool 0.50m wide which was in turned bordered by a narrower stripe, 16mm wide of goat hair which formed the rug edge. The goat hair band alternates light and dark hair warps to achieve an alternating light and dark horizontal bar patterning.Before conservation, January 2007.

description.value: Several fragments of a brown, dark brown and natural-coloured wool mantle. The weave is plain and weft-predominant. The spinning direction of warp and weft is 's'. The thread count is warp 6 per 10mm and weft 12 and 20 per 10mm. The selvedge is reinforced with 2  and 3 warp cords and the edges are 's'-cord. There are natural coloured bands at either end and alternating bands of brown and dark brown in the centre. Selvedge patterns are present at both edges and consist of blue triangles edged in natural colour, with a natural coloured tassel, embroidered on a dark brown background.

description.value: Several fragments of a natural-coloured wool textile, probably originally part of a pair of trousers, used as wrapping. The weave is plain and weft-face. The spinning direction of warp and weft is 's'. The thread count is warp 7 per 10mm and weft 18 per 10mm. The selvedge is reinforced with 2 warp cords. The hem at the waist is 35mm wide and there is a 'v'-shaped opening for a cord. The seams are flat-felled. Some areas have been darned with paired natural-coloured 's'-spun wool thread and appear similar to basket-weave. The seams are sewn with wool thread, while the hem is sewn with cotton thread. Both consist of 2 's'-spun elements, 'z'-plied.

description.value:
Seven fragments of textile, cord and leather:
1. the leather (55x20mm) has traces of red ochre;
2. the cord is of dark brown/black hair (2 ply Z);
3. three textile fragments are dark brown wool, warp-1 ply S, dia. 1mm; weft-brown wool, 1 ply S, dia. 1mm; c.8x8tpc;
4. one textile fragment is of buff wool in a loose plain weave, warp-1 ply S, dia. 1 mm; weft-1 ply S, dia. 0.5mm; c.8x12tpc; some double picks; evidence of sewing with a dark brown yarn (1 ply S, dia. 1mm);
5. the other textile is a bundle of brown wool, loose plain weave; warp and weft-1 ply S crepe, dia. 1mm; tpc n/a; all edges ragged.

description.value: Numerous fragments of a natural, yellow-tan coloured woven wool loin-cloth, fabric type B. The spinning direction of the warp and weft is 's' and the weave is plain and weft-predominant. The thread count is 5 warp and 19 weft per 10mm. The selvedge is reinforced with 2 warp cords. Originally triangular in shape, the narrow end is finished with 30mm of countered twining (approx. 14 rows) ending in a fringe 125mm long, knotted at the end. The fringe consists of two elements that are 's'-spun and the fringe elements are approximately 30mm in length. The wide upper end is finished with a 's'-twisted cord. A sturdy rectangular patch was attached at the wide top of the cloth to the 's' cord and neatly stitched along the selvedges to the back. The raw edge is turned under at the bottom. Whip stitches attached the patch. The garment appears mended roughly on the interior also. The sewing thread consists of 2 's'-spun and 'z'-plied natural wool threads.

description.value: Fragment of a red sprang hair-net with an openwork pattern of diagonal lozenges. An undyed top-sewn linen seam preserves a border of lozenges in green and yellow wool on one side, and a brow band of top-sewn black plaited wool runs across the top. The original upper edge remains, with selvedges in the seam.  The thread is S-spun and Z-ply. The wool warp is c. 12 threads per cm; the linen warp is c. 12 threads per cm. The black plaited wool is S-spun, 3-ply and Z-ply.

description.value: Tunic; linen; with applied tapestry ornament; the front and back both have two vertical stripes (clavi) terminating in medallions, and connected at the neck by broader transverse bands; below each of the stripes is a larger medallion (orbiculus or segmentum), while a similar medallion is on each shoulder; apart from the horizontal bands, which have animals in different arrangements, only two designs are used, one for the stripes, the other for the medallions; the stripes have a series of superimposed panels within conventional borders containing figures, and the central panel represents the Virgin and Child; the larger medallion has the Adoration of the Magi.
